1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ As evidenced by my other course, this is my recommendation for white and I still think it is one of the most critical tests of the Grunfeld. White's intention is to grab the whole centre with e4, while not allowing black to get central counterplay after ...Nd5xc3. Naturally, since this is were my two repertoires 'face off' against each other, it is impossible to find total equality for black and an advantage for white at the same time. At some point, with good play, white's advantage will be neutralised - it just depends how long this takes. I looked through my 3. f3 course and searched for positions with a slight white edge, and then just extended the analysis a bit until it is closer to equality. Of course, and this goes without saying, the lines remain fully playable for both sides. }
3... Nc6
{ A very modern choice, and the one I said I would most likely use in my 3. f3 course  (from white's perspective)  . It is challenging, tricky and keeps the game out of King's Indian territory  (which is a bonus since this is a Grunfeld course)  . White must be careful not to expect to kick black's knights around and win instantly. Black's defence is sound. Our idea is to play on the dark squares and exploit the early f3. We intends to play ...e5 and sometimes even . ..Bc5 while running amok on the dark squares which white has weakened. }
4. d5
{ A vital move. White kicks black's knight away before he can implement any . ..e5 ideas. Black has a good game without much fuss after either of the alternatives. }
4... Ne5 5. e4 d6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. f4
{ An important move, kicking the knight back. The knight can't go to g4, since we would kick it back even further with h3. }
7... Ned7 8. Nh3
{ A very strong and interesting move which has been played repeatedly by Grischuk and recommended by Svetushkin. You might be wondering why not to f3 instead ? h3 isn't the final destination for white's knight ! It is going to f2 next, where it can support the very important e4 pawn. f3 does look more active, but does not help protect e4. In this position, black fundamentally has 3 plans: 1. The ...e5 break  (played while the knight is still on d7)  . This forces an interesting structure after dxe6.2. The ...c6 break usually involves queenside play such as ...Qa5/Qb6 and ...Nc5.3. Black plays flexibly and keeps his options open. This has the added benefit of allowing ...e6  (after ...Nc5)  , after which taking on e6 is ill-advised since black can recapture with his bishop. I have chosen to go with the 3rd of these plans. }
8... O-O
