[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The 3.g3 Fianchetto Grunfeld"]
[Black "Bg2 Nf3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ The fianchetto variation of the Grunfeld. It was recommended by Avrukh in his 1. d4 book series. White intends to get a slight but safe edge against both the King's Indian and Grunfeld. }
3... d5
{ The alternative was c6 which was recommended by Avrukh as well, but this time in his Grunfeld series. Those lead to symmetrical positions though, which I generally dislike, so I opted for the more lively ...d5. 3...d5 is the recommendation in 'The Safest Grunfeld', an excellent Grunfeld book which was the inspiration for much of this Fianchetto Grunfeld chapter. }
4. Bg2 { This is more flexible than 4. Nf3. } 4... Bg7
{ In this position, there are 3 key variations. 1. Nf3 without having inserted cxd5. This will be met by dxc4 followed by c3 in Grunfeld-style. 2. cxd5 with the idea of e4 + Ne2. This leads to Modern Benoni-like positions after ... c5 and black shouldn't be worried if he knows a bit of theory. 3. Finally, 5. cxd5 followed by the normal 6. Nf3 is the mainline. }
5. Nf3
{ The first of 3 possible setups. White has decided not to take on d5 and has rather played his knight to f3. }
5... dxc4
{ The correct moveorder. Playing 5...O-O and white responding with 6. cxd5 would not allow my suggested line against the Nf3+ cxd5 mainline. }
6. Qa4+
{ As mentioned previously, regaining the c4 pawn with the queen is usually not too challenging. }
6... Nc6 7. Qxc4 Nd7
{ Black realises that the knight is better on b6 and that the queen is a target. }
8. O-O Nb6 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Rd1 Bf5
{ Black lures white's pawn to e4 so that he can attack d4. } 11. e4 Bg4
{ The d4 pawn is sorely lacking protection. } 12. d5 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nd4
{ Black has a very comfortable position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The 3.g3 Fianchetto Grunfeld"]
[Black "Bg2 Nf3 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ The fianchetto variation of the Grunfeld. It was recommended by Avrukh in his 1. d4 book series. White intends to get a slight but safe edge against both the King's Indian and Grunfeld. }
3... d5
{ The alternative was c6 which was recommended by Avrukh as well, but this time in his Grunfeld series. Those lead to symmetrical positions though, which I generally dislike, so I opted for the more lively ...d5. 3...d5 is the recommendation in 'The Safest Grunfeld', an excellent Grunfeld book which was the inspiration for much of this Fianchetto Grunfeld chapter. }
4. Bg2 { This is more flexible than 4. Nf3. } 4... Bg7
{ In this position, there are 3 key variations. 1. Nf3 without having inserted cxd5. This will be met by dxc4 followed by c3 in Grunfeld-style. 2. cxd5 with the idea of e4 + Ne2. This leads to Modern Benoni-like positions after ... c5 and black shouldn't be worried if he knows a bit of theory. 3. Finally, 5. cxd5 followed by the normal 6. Nf3 is the mainline. }
5. Nf3
{ The first of 3 possible setups. White has decided not to take on d5 and has rather played his knight to f3. }
5... dxc4
{ The correct moveorder. Playing 5...O-O and white responding with 6. cxd5 would not allow my suggested line against the Nf3+ cxd5 mainline. }
6. Na3 c3
{ The true Grunfeld move. It has gradually overtaken the O-O 7.O-O Nc6 8. Nxc4 Be6 line. The c3 line does strengthen the white centre, but it also comes with a few advantages. It closes the c file and means that c3 becomes a possible target for black. Due to this c4 becomes a key square and a big goal in black's plan is to occupy it with a piece, usually the knight. Black wants to play actively here with c5, but must be careful not to allow the advance of pawns to e4, d5 and c4 respectively. }
7. bxc3 c5 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne5 Nc6
{ A standard tactical motif. Black sacrifices a pawn to exchange the knight and get the initiative. }
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Bh3
{ White's position is quite difficult, mainly due to black's strong initiative thanks to his mate threats on the light squares. }
12. Re1 Nd5
{ Cutting the bishop off and threatening the c3 pawn. Rc8 is fine too. } 13.
Bxd5 Qxd5 14. e4 Qd7
{ Black has more than enough compensation here. White's king's situation is shaky  (with very weak light squares)  and d4 is under heavy fire. }
*

