{ White's hopes for an advantage rest with this move. His plan is extremely simple - he will develop his pieces naturally and then put his central majority of pawns into motion. This does sound very scary, but black has good play if he knows the ideas. Key to black's success is the weakness of the e4, d3 and c4 squares - c4 in particular. Due to this he will be mainly playing on the light squares. He would love to get a knight or pawn to c4  (no need to rush the c5 pawns advance, though)  so controlling c4 is critical. He would also like to get a bishop to e4 via f5, locking down on the light squares and creating a rather powerful blockade. Black's queen could be placed actively on the queenside, or maybe on h5  (via d5)  . The whole point of this general scheme is to lock down and blockade white's central majority, leaving him with no counterplay. Black likes to play against the bishop which will come to b2. By playing on the light squares, he will make this bishop bad. Often black would love to trade off the knights, leaving white's bad bishops and allowing black to take full advantage of white's weaknesses. Now, what to do in this actual position... Black would like to start off by developing his light bishop to f5. Then the queen should be placed on the queenside or h5  (a bishop battery, Be6 and Qc8, is also possible)  . Black should strive for minor piece and queen exchanges, which favour black. At the right moment, black will want to play c4 or cxd4  (if he has a commanding control of the c file.)  . Don't hurry the c5 pawn ! Note the other options for white on move 9 aren't too dangerous. }
