[White "The 3.g3 Fianchetto Grunfeld"]
[Black "Bg2 and cxd5 5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ The fianchetto variation of the Grunfeld. It was recommended by Avrukh in his 1. d4 book series. White intends to get a slight but safe edge against both the King's Indian and Grunfeld. }
3... d5
{ The alternative was c6 which was recommended by Avrukh as well, but this time in his Grunfeld series. Those lead to symmetrical positions though, which I generally dislike, so I opted for the more lively ...d5. 3...d5 is the recommendation in 'The Safest Grunfeld', an excellent Grunfeld book which was the inspiration for much of this Fianchetto Grunfeld chapter. }
4. Bg2 { This is more flexible than 4. Nf3. } 4... Bg7
{ In this position, there are 3 key variations. 1. Nf3 without having inserted cxd5. This will be met by dxc4 followed by c3 in Grunfeld-style. 2. cxd5 with the idea of e4 + Ne2. This leads to Modern Benoni-like positions after ... c5 and black shouldn't be worried if he knows a bit of theory. 3. Finally, 5. cxd5 followed by the normal 6. Nf3 is the mainline. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 Nb6 7. Ne2 c5
{ Black has to play the move now. Move order is very important. } 8. d5 O-O 9.
O-O e6
{ Now theory splits into two parts. Nbc3 and Nec3. Black's e6 move is a common idea in the Grunfeld to try and bring about the downfall of white pawn centre. Black's light bishop is a minor problem. Putting it on f5 is possible, but it is a bit unstable after a possible h3 and g4. Therefore black will probably put it on b7  (after moving the b pawn of course.)  . Let me mention a few general ideas and plans of these positions. Black should avoid at all costs a position where he has exchanged on d5 too early and then white marches his pawn to d6. Having a pawn on d6 is not only a nuisance for black, but it also opens the Bg2's diagonal and frees up the d5 square for the knight. If black doesn't take on d5 too early, and white pushes d5-d6 right away, he could find it becomes quite vulnerable, because the typical Bf4  (to protect d6)  would be met by ...e5. Black, as a guideline, should keep the central tension until white defines the future of his knights or plays Bf4. The point about the knights is that he cannot keep it on e2 forever - it does nothing. Therefore there are 3 typical knight combinations for white: Ne2-c3+Na3, Ne2-c3+Nd2 and Nbc3+Nf4. The first 2 options move whites pieces away from the kingside and black should open the centre and try take the initiative. With the knight on f4 however, we should close it down with e5 and head for a good closed game with a possible knight on d6 and f5 in the future. Finally, a rather key point to remember is the weakness of the d3 square for white. Black can try attack it with ...Bf5 and ...Na6-b4-d3. This can be lifesaving in some situations. And always look out for tactical threats thanks to the Bishop on g7. }
10. Nec3 { One of two possible lines. The other is Nbc3. } 10... Na6
{ Cleverly delaying the capture of d5, or maybe even omitting it. This is important because it keeps the option of ...e5 open, which might the followed up with putting a knight on d6 via c4 or c8. This allows play on both sides of the board, with b5 and f5 possible. }
11. a4 exd5 12. exd5 Nc4
{ This is an interesting move. Black toys with the idea of ...Nc4-e5 followed by invading on d3 after ...Nb4. }
13. Na3 Ne5 14. Ne4 Bg4 { White's queen is short on good squares. } 15. f3 Bf5
{ Black has a nice position - he will want to play ...Nb4 after protecting the c5 pawn. }
*

