{ In this position, there are 3 key variations. 1. Nf3 without having inserted cxd5. This will be met by dxc4 followed by c3 in Grunfeld-style. 2. cxd5 with the idea of e4 + Ne2. This leads to Modern Benoni-like positions after ... c5 and black shouldn't be worried if he knows a bit of theory. 3. Finally, 5. cxd5 followed by the normal 6. Nf3 is the mainline. }
5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 { The third and mainline option against our setup. } 6...
Nb6
{ Once again, moveorder is very important. ...c5 ideas are equal at the very best for black. We don't want to play drawish equal lines where we have no real winning chances. That's why we aim for e5 ideas which give dynamic positions which are unbalanced and both sides have their trumps. }
7. Nc3 Nc6 8. e3
{ White is almost forced to protect the d4-pawn with 8. e3 since 8. d5 hangs a pawn after Bxc3+. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ A seemingly strange move. e5 could be played straight away, so there is seemingly no need for such a preparatory move. e5 immediately would be met by 10. d5 which is not pleasant for black. Ask the Bishop on g7. But if we look it at the position from white's point of view, the e3 + d4 pawn structure is even more restricting for the Bishop on c1 than our one on g7 ! So white's idea to develop the Bc1 must be b3 and Bb2, followed by moves like Qe2 and developing the rooks. If this is allowed without any black counterplay, like the move e5, we would be worse off. So since c5 isn't possible, we must play for e5. The only question is when to play e5. The answer is to play it when d5 is not available to white. So lets make a useful improving "pass" move while we wait. Now white has two options: 10. Re1 and 10. d5 }
10. Re1
{ Using a very similar wait-and-see strategy. White plans to counter black's e pawn advance with the advance of his own e and f pawns. }
10... a5
{ Another useful move, planning to advance a4-a3 to create weaknesses or maybe activate the rook through a5. This is the critical position, where white has about a dozen playable moves. }
11. b3
{ This seems like a normal way to develop, but the problem is that it weakens the long diagonal temporarily. }
11... e5 { Exploiting the fact that d5 fails to ... e4 !. } 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxe5 15. Bb2 c6 { Black has achieved comfortable equality. }
*

