7. dxc6 { This is a slightly inaccurate version of the 7. Rc1 finesse. } 7...
Bxd4
{ The key difference is that ...Bxd4 is strong here - there is no c7 counter as in 7. Rc1. }
8. cxb7 Bxb7 9. Rc1 O-O
{ Of course, when compared to 7. Rc1, the existence of the queens favours black due to his development lead. }
10. e3 Bxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Qa5 12. Nf3 Rd8 13. Qc1 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nd7
{ Black has fantastic play for the pawn of course. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bg5 Variations"]
[Black "4. Bg5 Bg7 5.Bxf6 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ White develops his bishop actively and threatens to win the d5 pawn. Black has 2 options. The mainline of Ne4 or the interesting Bg7. I've never been fully satisfied with the positions after Ne4, even though they are probably equal. This led me to search for some interesting alternatives and I'm happy with what I found. Note that I've covered 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 under the move order of 4. Bg5 Bg7 5. Nf3. }
4... Bg7
{ So what is black's idea ? Well, nothing fancy. Black ignores white's threat to win a pawn  (with Bxf6)  and simply develops. There's a decent chance that this will catch some white players off guard. I, for one, didn't know this was playable until quite recently. Playable it definitely is though, and it has been used by super GMs like Vachier Lagraeve and Grischuk, amongst others. White has a couple of options. Of course, 5. Bxf6 is the critical test of black's opening since it grabs a pawn. 5. Nf3 transposes into a variation which usually arises after 4. Nf3. e3 is something quite likely to be played by someone caught unawares by Bg7. Finally, 4. cxd5 is going to transpose into a rare line of the Exchange Variation which is covered elsewhere. }
5. Bxf6
{ This looks very natural and has been the most popular choice in practice. White removes the defender and wins the d5-pawn. }
5... Bxf6 6. cxd5 { This is the correct way to capture the pawn. } 6... c6
{ The pawn on d4 blocks black's access to the d4-pawn, so it's natural to get rid of it and speed up development. }
7. e4
{ White logically wants to hold on to his d5 pawn. Black has tried a number of moves here, like ...O-O, ...Qb6, ...cxd5 and ...Bg7. }
7... O-O
{ I like the simplicity of this. Black can bide his time and make a useful move. The thing is that white can't really do the same - his next move will be commital in some way. }
8. e5 { This should be black's critical test. } 8... Bg7 9. Bc4
{ White's clearly trying to hold on to his pawn. } 9... b5
{ This ...b5 lunge is a major benefit of the c6-pawn. } 10. Bb3 b4 11. Nce2
{ The knight can go to a4, but this is not so threatening. Black will play in French style and eventually make the freeing .. .f6 break. }
11... cxd5 { Black has regained his pawn. } 12. h4
{ This appears to be white's idea - a kingside attack. Black should take some care, but objectively the attack is not so dangerous. }
12... Nc6
{ The general idea here is to generate rapid queenside counterplay and put an end to white's attack via exchanges. }
13. Rc1 Qb6 14. h5
{ Taking the d5-pawn would only ease black's central counterplay  (it would open both the d-file and the a8-h1 diagonal)  . }
14... Rd8
{ Protecting the pawn is a good idea in any case - it allows provides the king an escape square on f8 if worst comes to worst. }
15. Bc2 Ba6
{ An important move. A bishop on a6 basically kills white's attack before it even gets going, since it is very difficult to get the pieces to the kingside without exchanges. }
16. Bd3 { White's trying to shift the queen to h3 somehow. } 16... Rdc8 17. Nf3
Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nd8
{ White's attack is dead and mass exchanges loom, which favour black of course. }
