10... Nxe5 { Black has no illusions about the scary-looking Nxe7+. } 11. Nxe7+
Kh8 12. Nxg6+ fxg6 13. Bxd8 Rxd8 14. Qa4 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Bxd4
{ We reach one of the crucial positions for this varaition. 3 pieces are usually more than sufficient for the queen, but white's extra pawn makes the position more interesting. I realised that black has a pleasant position after some analysis. He basically needs to do 2 things, which is solidify the position of the bishop on d4, and develop. Moves like ... Nc6, ...Bf5, ...Rd7 and ...Re8 are normal. Sometimes, white might want to play f3+ g4. It's best to prevent this with ...h5  (and ...h4 if white persists with h3)  . }
