6. e4
{ Grabbing the whole centre is always the critical test of ...dxc4 ideas. }
6... c5 7. d5
{ This seems normal and good. It has been white's most popular move. White wants to secure his space edge and regain the c4 pawn. }
7... b5
{ This typical idea makes things far trickier for white. Now regaining the c4 pawn is far from simple. }
8. e5 b4
{ Black must counterattack white's knight or risk getting run over in the centre. }
9. exf6 exf6 10. Qe2+ Kf8 11. Bf4 bxc3 12. bxc3 Qxd5 13. Qxc4 Qc6
{ At the moment, black is a pawn up, which white must spend time to recoup. }
14. Be3 Kg8 15. Qxc5 Qxc5 16. Bxc5 f5
{ Black definitely has the more comfortable side of this endgame, mostly because c3 is a pretty serious weakness at the moment. He can unravel his kingside with something like ...Bf6 and ...Kg7. }
