[White "Bg5 Variations"]
[Black "4. Bg5 Bg7 5.Nf3 10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ White develops his bishop actively and threatens to win the d5 pawn. Black has 2 options. The mainline of Ne4 or the interesting Bg7. I've never been fully satisfied with the positions after Ne4, even though they are probably equal. This led me to search for some interesting alternatives and I'm happy with what I found. Note that I've covered 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 under the move order of 4. Bg5 Bg7 5. Nf3. }
4... Bg7
{ So what is black's idea ? Well, nothing fancy. Black ignores white's threat to win a pawn  (with Bxf6)  and simply develops. There's a decent chance that this will catch some white players off guard. I, for one, didn't know this was playable until quite recently. Playable it definitely is though, and it has been used by super GMs like Vachier Lagraeve and Grischuk, amongst others. White has a couple of options. Of course, 5. Bxf6 is the critical test of black's opening since it grabs a pawn. 5. Nf3 transposes into a variation which usually arises after 4. Nf3. e3 is something quite likely to be played by someone caught unawares by Bg7. Finally, 4. cxd5 is going to transpose into a rare line of the Exchange Variation which is covered elsewhere. }
5. Nf3
{ Once I became satisfied with Bg7, I realised this move/moveorder could be a problem. Since I wanted to avoid ...Ne4 ideas, I was forced to search for alternatives I didn't actually know existed  (until recently)  . Fortunately, there was a move I ended up being very happy with: dxc4. }
5... dxc4
{ Besides the obvious practical benefits this has  (not as well-known, etc.)  , I think this is very strong. It brings black a positive win rate and fresh, interesting play which is also objectively good. It has a healthy grandmaster following, so it is no one-trick pony. }
6. e4
{ Grabbing the whole centre is always the critical test of ...dxc4 ideas. }
6... c5 7. d5
{ This seems normal and good. It has been white's most popular move. White wants to secure his space edge and regain the c4 pawn. }
7... b5
{ This typical idea makes things far trickier for white. Now regaining the c4 pawn is far from simple. }
8. d6 { White is trying to blow open the centre to his advantage. } 8... Bb7
{ Black must simply ignore the pawn for now. The pawn on d6 doesn't really threaten anything, and moreover the bishop on b7 allows black to meet e5 with . ..Ne4. }
9. e5 { After this, the game becomes very unusual and concrete. } 9... Ne4
{ Black makes use of his previous move. } 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. a4
{ White is of course trying to undermine the protection of the c4 pawn. } 11...
a6 { Black can't allow white to regain the c4 pawn and develop his bishop. }
12. Bxe7 Qa5+ 13. Nd2
{ Material is equal at the moment. White's d6 pawn looks terrifying, but in fact it can be easily blockaded. Black's problem here is that he can't easily castle. Fortunately, there are ways to play around this. }
13... Bh6 { The bishop is very well-placed here. Black threatens ...c3. } 14.
Ra3
{ This is logical - black prevents ...c4 and tries to activate his rook. Also, white threatens axb5 since the rook is protected now. }
14... Qb4 15. Rh3 Bf4
{ Taking on d2 is a bit premature - black should only play this when he really has no other option. Keeping the tension is in his favour. }
16. Rh4
{ The rook now forces the exchange, but the h4 square is worse than h3. } 16...
Bxd2+ 17. Qxd2 Bd5
{ It's important that black keeps the tension with the queens now. White can't unravel easily without taking our queen, but this makes our queenside majority a formidable threat. Black is doing well here. Next he will play moves like ... Be6, ...Nc6/d7 and develop his pieces. }
