[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations"]
[Black "5.Nf3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Rc1
{ A line assessed as not too challenging. Black has 2 good options: c5 or dxc4. Note that 6. e3 here would transpose to 5. e3. }
6... dxc4 { Between 6.. .c5 and dxc4, this is the more fighting option. } 7. e3
{ A bit less ambitious than e4. White solidifies d4 and plans to regain c4. }
7... Be6
{ Black should make it as tricky as possible for white to get the pawn back. }
8. Ng5 Bd5
{ This exploits the unfortunate position of white's bishop on f4  (since after Nxd5 ... Nxd5 the bishop is attacked)  . }
9. e4 h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5
{ with rough equality. Black plans to retreat his knight to b6 and use the other one to invade d4 via c6. }
