1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Rc1
{ A line assessed as not too challenging. Black has 2 good options: c5 or dxc4. Note that 6. e3 here would transpose to 5. e3. }
6... dxc4 { Between 6.. .c5 and dxc4, this is the more fighting option. } 7. e4
{ Certainly more ambitious but this also gives black play against d4. } 7...
Bg4 8. Bxc4 Nh5 9. Be3 Bxf3 10. gxf3
{ Sacrificing the pawn is possible, but this move is most popular. } 10... e6
{ A decent alternative is e5, but this is a bit more interesting since more pieces remain on the board. This move has a couple of points. If given the chance, h4 is a good square for our queen. Another idea is to exploit white's obviously weak dark squares with a manoeuvre such as ...Nc6 and  (after d5)  ... Ne5. }
