[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations"]
[Black "5.Rc1 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. Rc1
{ This is white's third most common choice. He tries to pre-empt the c5 advance, but it will be played anyway with a little preparation }
5... Nh5
{ The idea behind this is not just to push the bishop back, but also to unveil our dark squared bishop. This adds some punch to the ...c5 break. Of course, the downside is that our knight is poorly placed on h5. }
6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 c5 { This move is even stronger with our bishop unveiled. } 8.
e3 cxd4 9. Nxd5 Nc6 10. Be2 g5
{ This move works well tactically. It not only attacks the dark bishop, but also traps white's knight ! }
11. Bxh5 e6
{ We rather want to gain the knight - black doesn't have to destroy his own pawn structure that way. }
12. Bg3 exd5 { Black's doing very well here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations"]
[Black "5.e3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3
{ White's most unpleasant option. White keeps the option of Ne2, supporting the Knight on c3 open. }
5... O-O
{ Black foregoes the possibility of playing a quick c5. As is often the case in these variations, ...c5 often dissolves into positions which are symmetrical and difficult to play for a win. Black usually has to tread a fine line to achieve complete equality. }
6. Rc1
{ A logical move. White pre-empts the opening of the long diagonal and realises the knight on c3 might come under fire. }
6... Be6
{ Black exploits the fact that white isn't in the best position to exploit the bishop on e6 with ... Ng5. Note that 7. Nf3 dxc4 now would transpose to 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Rc1. }
7. Qb3 { White takes advantage of the undefended b7-pawn. } 7... c5
{ No fear ! Black realises that taking the pawn costs white time. } 8. Qxb7 Qb6
{ Following one of Nimzowitch's principles of not only losing the piece when that piece is exchanged, but the tempi invested in it as well. Note that the queen is trapped after Qxa8 ...Nc6 and white's position would soon fall apart. }
9. Qxb6 axb6
{ The other concrete reason for this exchange is the opening of the a-file, which is another avenue of counterplay for black. Black's development edge ensures that black should win the pawn back, with interest. }
*

