[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations"]
[Black "5.e3 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3
{ White's most unpleasant option. White keeps the option of Ne2, supporting the Knight on c3 open. }
5... O-O
{ Black foregoes the possibility of playing a quick c5. As is often the case in these variations, ...c5 often dissolves into positions which are symmetrical and difficult to play for a win. Black usually has to tread a fine line to achieve complete equality. }
6. cxd5
{ Many people encountering 5...O-O for the first time would notice it 'loses a pawn'. Some white players go for it, but it usually just leads to trouble for him because black builds up a large development lead. }
6... Nxd5 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Bxc7 { It's a bit late for white to opt out. } 8...
Na6 9. Bxa6
{ Instead, retreating the dark bishop can lead to big problems after e5. } 9...
Qxg2 10. Qf3 Qxf3 11. Nxf3 bxa6
{ After a nearly forced line, an interesting position is reached. Black has regained his pawn, but he has doubled a-pawns. As compensation black possesses the bishop pair. }
12. Rc1 f6
{ This seems like a fairly simple option to take the e5 square away from white's knight. An interesting alternative is a5 with the idea of freeing up the a6 square for the bishop. }
