{ With white having committed is knight, now we should play ...c5. The idea becomes apparent on the next move. }
7. dxc5 Ne4
{ Qa5 is more popular but this move has been the choice of the World's elite over the last few years. Had this position arisen without the inclusion of Ng1-f3 and ...O-O, white could have replied here with Ng1-e2. }
8. Be5 { This is a funny-looking move, but it has been played a few times. }
8... Bxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5
{ Black's already doing well - having tripled c-pawns is far from ideal. } 11.
Qb3 Qc7
{ An important subtelty - black forces a weakening. If the knight retreats, black takes on c4 and only then regains c5. }
12. f4 Qxc5 { Black's definitely slightly better here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations"]
[Black "5.e3 6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3
{ White's most unpleasant option. White keeps the option of Ne2, supporting the Knight on c3 open. }
5... O-O
{ Black foregoes the possibility of playing a quick c5. As is often the case in these variations, ...c5 often dissolves into positions which are symmetrical and difficult to play for a win. Black usually has to tread a fine line to achieve complete equality. }
6. Nf3 c5
{ With white having committed is knight, now we should play ...c5. The idea becomes apparent on the next move. }
7. dxc5 Ne4
{ Qa5 is more popular but this move has been the choice of the World's elite over the last few years. Had this position arisen without the inclusion of Ng1-f3 and ...O-O, white could have replied here with Ng1-e2. }
8. Rc1 { This is of course the standard move to reinforce the knight on c3. }
8... Nd7 9. cxd5 Qa5 { Piling up the pressure on c3. } 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. bxc3
Nxc5 12. e4 Bd7
{ Black's piece activity provides full compensation for the pawn. Next comes ...Ba4, ...e6 etc. }
