[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h4
{ An interesting improvement over the 4. h4 !?, since the idea of ...c5 dxc5 ...d4 doesn't work any more. }
5... dxc4
{ I think central play is the best counter to h4. If you take the focus off the kingside, then h4 makes less sense. }
6. e4 O-O 7. Bxc4 c5 { Black challenges the centre. } 8. d5 b5
{ This is an important tactical idea to remember. All of black's previous moves were leading up to this tactical idea. }
9. Bxb5 Nxe4
{ The idea reveals itself. Black will recoup the bishop on b5 with ...Qa5+. }
10. Nxe4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxb5
{ An interesting position is reached. Both sides are underdeveloped and white will have problems castling. On the other hand, black most take care on the kingside. }
13. h5 { If white doesn't continue with h4-h5, I don't see the point. } 13...
Qc4
{ The queen is well-placed here, where it attacks both c3 and d5 while retaining the option of swinging over to the kingside if need be. }
14. hxg6 fxg6
{ Play can go any number of ways here, as shown by the 4 practical games. Black is fine though. }
