[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.e3 & Sidelines"]
[Black "4.e3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ White's central idea behind this move is to prevent c5 or at least render it ineffective. White bolsters the d4 pawn and has a number of ways to play from this position. He can allow black to play c5, he can try stop it with b4, an idea of Makogonov, or he can hurry to castle. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bc4 Nb6
{ There's no need to strengthen white's centre further. } 7. Bb3 O-O 8. Nf3 c5
9. O-O
{ Taking on c5 is illogical since black's Grunfeld bishop becomes a monster and white can't hold on to c5 anyway. }
9... cxd4 10. exd4
{ We reach a fairly normal IQP position with a few differences. Black has fianchettoed instead of playing ... e6. This means that d4 is under heavier attack, but d5 is unprotected. Fortunately, the d5 'break' has little effect here. Also, white's standard plan of a kingside attack is going to fail from the get-go because of black's fianchetto structure. }
10... Bg4 11. d5 { White can't hold the pawn on d4 so it must advance. } 11...
N8d7 12. h3
{ Black threatened ...Ne5  (which would inflict white with doubled f-pawns)  . }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nc5
{ Black's position is very pleasant. The d-pawn is weak and white has few dynamic possibilities. }
*

