1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ White's central idea behind this move is to prevent c5 or at least render it ineffective. White bolsters the d4 pawn and has a number of ways to play from this position. He can allow black to play c5, he can try stop it with b4, an idea of Makogonov, or he can hurry to castle. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3 e6
{ I like this quirky little move which has been the choice of Caruana and Svidler. Black supports his d5 pawn, which makes the queen on b3 look silly. On the other hand, ...e6 and ...g6 together are usually a bad idea, and in this case the weakened dark squares can make castling tricky. }
6. Nf3 { This doesn't really challenge black. } 6... O-O 7. Be2 b6 8. O-O Bb7
9. Qc2 Qe7 10. Rd1 c5
{ The position is roughly equal, but black has the more comfortable position. }
