1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ White's central idea behind this move is to prevent c5 or at least render it ineffective. White bolsters the d4 pawn and has a number of ways to play from this position. He can allow black to play c5, he can try stop it with b4, an idea of Makogonov, or he can hurry to castle. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3 e6
{ I like this quirky little move which has been the choice of Caruana and Svidler. Black supports his d5 pawn, which makes the queen on b3 look silly. On the other hand, ...e6 and ...g6 together are usually a bad idea, and in this case the weakened dark squares can make castling tricky. }
6. Qa3
{ I don't see the point of 5. Qb3 if white doesn't play this. White has to try make castling difficult for black. }
6... b6
{ Our idea to counter this is simple. White isn't really in a position to mount a crushing attack, so black has some time. His next moves will be ...Bb7, ... Nbd7, ...c5  (blocking the queen)  and ...O-O. }
7. cxd5
{ Keeping the tension no longer benefits white since he wants to develop his bishop. }
7... exd5 8. Nf3 Bb7 9. Be2
{ 9. Ne5 ideas are met with the typical ...Nf6-d7 !  (so that the knight on b8 covers the c6 square)  . }
9... Nbd7 10. O-O c5
{ Alternatively, black can play ... Bf8-g7 with a likely perpetual. ...c5 allows black to fight for the win, now that he can castle safely. }
