[White "Russian System - Qb3"]
[Black "4.Qa4  1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move is played with the idea of entering the Russian system, but first luring black's bishop to d7. }
4... Bd7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 Bg7
{ We have transposed to a variation of the Russian system, with the difference that black's bishop is on d7. This means black cannot use the same idea which I recommend in the mainline Russian - however, the bishop on d7 lends itself to other possibilities - namely ...b5. }
7. e4 O-O 8. e5
{ White tries to use the fact that the bishop on d7 blocks the knight's usual escape square, but this backfires. }
8... Be6
{ An important intermediate move which allows the knight to go to d5. } 9. exf6
{ Objectively better is to retreat the queen, but after ...Nd5 black is fine. }
9... Bxc4 10. fxg7 Kxg7 11. Bxc4 Qxd4 12. Be2 Nc6
{ While three pieces are often enough for the queen, black's extra 2 pawns give him the far better chances. }
*

