[White "Russian System - Qb3"]
[Black "5.Qb3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ The Russian System. White practically forces black to give up the centre with dxc4 and follows up with e4, grabbing the whole centre himself. Black has many, many possible options against this, including  (after ...dxc4 and ...O-O)  ...Na6, ...a6, ...Nc6 + ...Bg4 etc. My choice will be a cutting edge gambit line based on ...Nc6 and ...e5 which sacrifices a pawn or two in exchange for massive activity. The line is theoretically sound, interesting and gives black a positive win rate. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. Bf4
{ is not really played anymore. White's obviously targeting c7. } 7... Na6
{ I quite like this. The point is that the bishop on f4 will look silly once we play ...c5. }
8. e4 c5 9. d5
{ This isn't a time white should get materialistic - after 9. dxc5 black should regain the c6 pawn with a development advantage. }
9... e6
{ Black of course wants to open up the centre - especially the e-file. } 10. d6
{ Logically closing the position. } 10... Nb4 11. Rc1 b6
{ Black's setup is very sound. He has good squares for all his pieces and the d6-pawn isn't going anywhere. }
