[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ The Russian System. White practically forces black to give up the centre with dxc4 and follows up with e4, grabbing the whole centre himself. Black has many, many possible options against this, including  (after ...dxc4 and ...O-O)  ...Na6, ...a6, ...Nc6 + ...Bg4 etc. My choice will be a cutting edge gambit line based on ...Nc6 and ...e5 which sacrifices a pawn or two in exchange for massive activity. The line is theoretically sound, interesting and gives black a positive win rate. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nc6 8. Be2
{ This is the most popular  (and best)  move. d5 isn't great immediately since black's knight goes to a5 followed by ...c6. }
8... e5
{ This is enterprising pawn sacrifice is my repertoire recommendation. Bg4 was the recommendation of both GM Avrukh, and GMs Delchev and Agrest. It leads to far calmer waters than e5. My choice has been played far less than Bg4, but it has been played by half of the World's elite players. Players such as Giri, Aronian, Vachier Lagraeve, Nepomniachtchi and so on have all played this move. I think it is both interesting and objectively strong, while giving black very good winning chances. So, what's the idea ? These variations are very concrete, but in general black is trying to stake his claim to the centre with ...e5. If white takes the pawn, black can regain it with ...Nf6-g4xe5, so 9. d5 is critical. After this black plays Nd4, sacrificing a pawn for good this time. In exchange, black gets a massive lead in development, threats and the inititiative. }
9. d5 Nd4 { The whole point. The knight can hardly be ignored on d4. } 10. Nxd4
exd4 11. Qxd4 c6
{ This move threatens ...Nxd5. White has a number of ways to deal with this threat, including a handful of queen moves and 12. d6. }
12. Qd1
{ This move seems to be a slightly worse version of Qc4. White still wants to hold onto his pawn, but his queen on d1 is far less active than on c4. }
12... cxd5
{ With this move, black tries to isolate the d5 pawn and eventually win it. A common alternative is ...Re8, but this might be stronger. }
13. exd5 b5
{ This move is a very typical idea in this variation. In this case, the point is to deflect pieces from the protection of d5. }
14. Nxb5 Nxd5 15. O-O Bb7
{ At first, it appears as if black is down a clean pawn. However, once you began to look at ways white can unravel, you realise things are far from simple. For example, the pressure on b2 prevents white from developing his queenside for the next couple moves. Although the game can go in any number of directions here, the key thing is to keep up some pressure and continue developing/ attacking - especially the b2 pawn, so moves like ...Rb8 and ...Qf6 are normal. The following is one sample line: }
16. Bf3 a6 17. Na3 { The knight is heading to c4  (so that it covers b2)  . }
17... Rb8 18. Nc4
{ White is trying to develop his bishop. Black's compensation for the pawn lies in the fact that protecting b2  (so the bishop can move)  is not so simpe. }
18... Qc7
{ Black needs to keep up the pressure and he can do so with this little tactical idea. }
19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Rfd8 { White can't hold on to the knight. } 21. Qe4 Rd4
22. Qf3 Rxc4 23. Rb1 Rc2
{ Black has fantastic compensation for the pawn and is likely to regain it sooner or later with full equality. }
*

