1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ The Russian System. White practically forces black to give up the centre with dxc4 and follows up with e4, grabbing the whole centre himself. Black has many, many possible options against this, including  (after ...dxc4 and ...O-O)  ...Na6, ...a6, ...Nc6 + ...Bg4 etc. My choice will be a cutting edge gambit line based on ...Nc6 and ...e5 which sacrifices a pawn or two in exchange for massive activity. The line is theoretically sound, interesting and gives black a positive win rate. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nc6 8. Be2
{ This is the most popular  (and best)  move. d5 isn't great immediately since black's knight goes to a5 followed by ...c6. }
8... e5
{ This is enterprising pawn sacrifice is my repertoire recommendation. Bg4 was the recommendation of both GM Avrukh, and GMs Delchev and Agrest. It leads to far calmer waters than e5. My choice has been played far less than Bg4, but it has been played by half of the World's elite players. Players such as Giri, Aronian, Vachier Lagraeve, Nepomniachtchi and so on have all played this move. I think it is both interesting and objectively strong, while giving black very good winning chances. So, what's the idea ? These variations are very concrete, but in general black is trying to stake his claim to the centre with ...e5. If white takes the pawn, black can regain it with ...Nf6-g4xe5, so 9. d5 is critical. After this black plays Nd4, sacrificing a pawn for good this time. In exchange, black gets a massive lead in development, threats and the inititiative. }
9. d5 Nd4 { The whole point. The knight can hardly be ignored on d4. } 10. Nxd4
exd4 11. Qxd4 c6
{ This move threatens ...Nxd5. White has a number of ways to deal with this threat, including a handful of queen moves and 12. d6. }
12. Qc4
{ White does nothing fancy here - he steps out of the discovered attack and intends to solidify his d5 pawn. This has been the most popular move and it is the critical test. }
12... b5
{ This enterprising idea appears to have first been pioneered by Maxime Vachier-Lagraeve. Black sacrifices a second pawn for extremely rapid development and threats on white's queen. And if white gets cold feet and decides to decline the pawn, then ...b5 is a very useful addition  (mostly since the bishop can come to b7)  . }
13. Qxc6
{ Taking the pawn is the most challenging, as it often is. In exchange, black receives quick development, targets  (e4 especially)  and an exposed white queen. }
13... Bd7 14. Qd6
{ This is probably the square where the queen is least vulnerable, but it can still be hit by ideas of ...Re8 and ...Bf8  (often after ...a5 is played)  . }
14... Re8 { Very simple, natural play. The rook develops and attacks e4. } 15.
Bg5
{ White indirectly defends e4 using a pin. This could be white's best 'objective' path, since he usually is able to keep his extra pawn in a position with opposite coloured bishops  (although black still has close to full compensation)  . }
15... b4
{ This decoy has featured elsewhere in this variation - the queen is lured this time to b4 which facilitates more clever tactics. }
16. Qxb4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxg5 18. O-O Rab8 19. Qd6 Bh3
{ After this virtually forced variation, black is going to regain one of his two sacrificed pawns while retaining the more active pieces. Out of 6 games, black has a score of 3.5, so practically his chances seem to be good here. }
20. Nf4
{ White forces an exchange of minor pieces, but this does lead to an opposite coloured bishop ending. }
20... Bg4 21. Bxg4 Be5 22. Qd7 Qxf4 23. g3 Qf6
{ White is of course slightly for choice here. Black will regain one of his pawns, while retaining active pieces. The opposite coloured bishops, however, mean that the draw is fairly simple to hold. So although this may be white's best 'objective' option here, black has had no problems in practice at all. }
