{ This move is a rather typical idea in this variation. Black's queen covers the a6 escape square and threatens to trap the queen with ...Bf8. Instead, the immediate a5 was played by So. This move packs a slightly larger punch though, since the queen is forced to a3 where it is more vulnerable to ...a5 + ...b4 plans. }
18. Qa3 a5
{ Black is already doing extremely well here. He has more than enough compensation for the pawns. Of course, the b5-pawn is taboo since e4 would hang. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Na4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The most challenging option for black in the Grunfeld and critical to the evaluation of the whole opening. White  (in most cases)  will follow up with e4, claiming the centre as his own. }
4... Nxd5
{ Of course, the main move is the natural follow-up e4, but there are a few alternatives. }
5. Na4
{ A very strange looking move, with an interesting idea. The idea is similar to 5. Bd2, white wants to avoid recapturing on c3 with a pawn. This line, though, is more problematic. The Knight is definitely not well placed on a4. The knight there has 3 options: 1  Take on b6. This exchange favours Black. 2  Go to c5 and attack b7. This takes too long and black can prevent it easily. 3  Return to c3. This just results in 2 tempi lost. }
5... Bg7 6. e4 Nb6 7. Be3 O-O
{ Black has almost completed development. The next step is to attack white's centre. }
8. Nf3 Bg4 9. Be2 Nc6 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nxa4 13. f4 e6
{ What black lacks in space he makes up for in threats and development. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Qb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The most challenging option for black in the Grunfeld and critical to the evaluation of the whole opening. White  (in most cases)  will follow up with e4, claiming the centre as his own. }
4... Nxd5
{ Of course, the main move is the natural follow-up e4, but there are a few alternatives. }
5. Qb3 { White forces Black to move the Knight. } 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7
{ In this position, it is not exactly clear what the Qb3 adds to the position. }
7. Ba3
{ White tries to prevent ...c5. All we have to do now is prepare it with ...b6. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 b6 9. e3
{ White plans to quickly finish development with ...Be2, ...O-O, ...Rac1 and ...Rfd1. Our idea to counter this is ...c5, ...Nc6 and play down the c-file. }
9... c5 10. Be2 Nc6 { Black has easy equality and a simple position to play. }
