[White "Exchange Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Bd2 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The most challenging option for black in the Grunfeld and critical to the evaluation of the whole opening. White  (in most cases)  will follow up with e4, claiming the centre as his own. }
4... Nxd5
{ Of course, the main move is the natural follow-up e4, but there are a few alternatives. }
5. Bd2
{ A rather quiet move by White. The idea is to neutralise black's typical idea used for counterplay i.e. ...Nxc3 followed by ...c5. White wants to recapture on c3 with his bishop, to counter black's strong bishop. Unfortunately for white, the bishop is quite misplaced on d2 and we can take advantage of this by simply retreating our knight. }
5... Bg7 6. e4 Nb6
{ Taking on c3 is in fact perfectly fine as well. This move tries to exploit Bd2 a bit more though and it leads to slightly more interesting play. }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Bb5
{ This seems like a strange square for the bishop, but once you realise that ...a6 favours white  (protection of knight on b6 is weakened)  it makes sense. }
8... Bd7
{ This is surprisingly fairly rare. The exchange of bishops favours black so white usually retreats. }
9. Be2 e5 10. dxe5 Bxe5 *

