[Black "7.Qa4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The most challenging option for black in the Grunfeld and critical to the evaluation of the whole opening. White  (in most cases)  will follow up with e4, claiming the centre as his own. }
4... Nxd5
{ Of course, the main move is the natural follow-up e4, but there are a few alternatives. }
5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+
{ A clever idea by White, aimed against our typical plan with ...c5 and ...Nc6. The smallest concession for us now is to play Nd7 and follow-up with ...c5. It is really not too bad, as we can redeploy the knight easily to f6 or b6 with tempo. }
7... Nd7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bg5 { A more active square for the bishop than e3. }
9... c5 10. Rc1
{ The c-file will probably open in the near future, so this is the rook's best square. }
10... a6
{ This has the idea of ...b5, which works tactically because of Bxb5 ...Nb6. }
