[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Sidelines"]
[Black "7.Bb5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
{ The most challenging option for black in the Grunfeld and critical to the evaluation of the whole opening. White  (in most cases)  will follow up with e4, claiming the centre as his own. }
4... Nxd5
{ Of course, the main move is the natural follow-up e4, but there are a few alternatives. }
5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bb5+
{ Much like the other 7th move deviations, this tries to make ...c5 as difficult to achieve as possible. }
7... c6
{ Since we haven't played ...c5 yet though, we can switch plans to a different queenside expansion. Black will roll his queenside pawns, all the while gaining time on white's bishop. }
8. Ba4 O-O 9. Ne2
{ Black has 3 different pawn advances that are strong: b5, c5 and e5. } 9... e5
{ When possible, I often prefer the ...e5 advance to the ...c5 one simply because the resulting positions are different to normal Grunfeld lines. This variation has the added benefit of being strong. }
10. O-O Qe7
{ Vacating the d8 square for the rook and putting light pressure on e4. Black has a comfortable position. It may seem difficult to get black's knight into the game, but it can get to a good square on b6 via d7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange - Nf3 & Be3"]
[Black "8.Bb5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ The most natural move. Once considered an error due to the possibility for Black to pin the knight to ...Bg4, a few new ideas   namely  8.Rb1  catapulted it into the position of the mainline of the Grunfeld. Only recently has it been taken over by 8. Bc4 as it has been discovered that Black does have adequate resources for a good game after 8. Rb1. }
7... c5 8. Bb5+
{ This line is not the most ambitious and is often interpreted as a draw offer. }
8... Nc6
{ The objective best move, albeit quite drawish in some cases. Nd7 !? is an interesting option to try and win. }
9. O-O cxd4 10. cxd4 O-O 11. Be3 Bg4 12. Bxc6 bxc6
{ White has managed to give black a structural defect, which white will often win, while black will pick up the d4-pawn. }
13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Rc5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qd7
{ The weaknesses of d4 and c6 cancel out. } *

