[White "Exchange - Nf3 & Be3"]
[Black "8.Be3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ The most natural move. Once considered an error due to the possibility for Black to pin the knight to ...Bg4, a few new ideas   namely  8.Rb1  catapulted it into the position of the mainline of the Grunfeld. Only recently has it been taken over by 8. Bc4 as it has been discovered that Black does have adequate resources for a good game after 8. Rb1. }
7... c5 8. Be3 { The second biggest move. } 8... Qa5
{ For a while I played and analysed Bg4, which I still believe is strong, but the problem was that it ended up being too drawish in certain variations and theoretical problems arose in others. Notably, one of my mainlines curiously transposed to the pawn-grab variation of the 8. Rb1 exchange - white might have a slight edge there, but in any case, I prefer not to have my queen on a2. Instead, this variation leads to play akin to 8. Rb1 9. ..Nc6 exchange variation. }
9. Nd2 { An interesting idea - white prepares to meet ...Qxc3 with Rc1. } 9...
Bd7 { A move played with the idea of ...Ba4. } 10. Rc1
{ White hopes that black takes the bait on a2. } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6
{ Once again, I don't think black should go pawn-grabbing - it is better to activate his pieces. }
12. d5 Nd4 { Black has good piece play and white needs to take some care. } *

