8... O-O 9. Be2 Nc6
{ This move will be my choice for this repertoire. I think it is a nice compromise between the theoretical strength of cxd4 Qa5+ and the ease of playing bNc6 is both strong, doesn't have a huge amount of theory to it and it has no forced draws  (unlike cxd4 Qa5+)  . }
10. d5
{ Advancing the pawn is white's only good option. Covering d4 with Be3 only leads to trouble after ... Bg4. White exploits the fact that grabbing the c3-pawn is very risky  (dark-squared weaknesses)  . }
10... Ne5
{ As mentioned, taking on c3 is risking because of the resulting dark-squared weaknesses. }
11. Nxe5
{ Retreating the knight is too slow. Black was ready to play the thematic ...f5. }
11... Bxe5 12. Qd2
{ A seemingly-odd square for the queen but the important point is that it covers the f4 square against the possibility of ...Qc7 + ...Bf4 and it also keeps d5 covered  (which is important because ...e6 is quite likely)  . }
12... e6 { We get to work right immediately at breaking down White's centre. }
13. f4 { The only try for an advantage. } 13... Bc7
{ A rather deep move. A more natural alternative is Bg7. The idea of this move is to prevent c3-c4. Our bishop will go to a5 where it will perform this role splendidly. As a knock-on effect, the White dark-squared bishop will be trapped in since the pawn will be on c3. The only way to activate it will be g4 and f5 but this will leave White's king a little exposed. The downside of this move is that the best and only defender of our king leaves for the queenside. Our king and especially those dark squares around him are a little bit vulnerable. }
14. O-O exd5 15. exd5 Ba5
{ The point of Black's plan. c3-c4 should be prevented at all costs. This is a huge branching point and a key position for the whole variation. }
16. d6 { The critical move. White gains space and hampers Black's pieces. }
16... Rb8
{ Black protects the b pawn  (freeing his bishop of this duty)  and toys with the idea of ...b5 at some point. }
17. Ba3 { White tries to build up an initiative. } 17... Bf5 18. Rbd1 Qf6
{ This leads almost by force to a drawn endgame. The alternative is Rc8 which leads to sharper play. }
19. Bxc5 Bxc3 20. Bd4
{ Other moves are not very good. The queen will become a target. } 20... Bxd4+
21. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 22. Rxd4 Rfd8 { Black has fully equalised. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange - Bc4 & Ne2"]
[Black "10.Rc1 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ This, followed up by 8. Ne2, is considered to be one of, if not the main lines of the Grunfeld. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2
{ White's agressive setup is one of his most promising in the Grunfeld. His pieces all develop naturally, like ...Be3, ... Qd2, ...O-O and ...Rc1 etc. He is now very well-placed to take support the centre and keep it. This whole setup gives Black other options as well though - like putting the bishop on c4 makes it vulnerable to ideas such as ...Na5. }
8... c5
{ Other ideas, such as ...b6 and ...Nc6 are slow and not very critical. } 9.
Be3 Nc6 10. Rc1
{ Once popular in the '80s due to guys like Polugaevsky, this system has been on the decline due to Black finding a good setup against it: }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Kf1 Qa3
{ The queen fulfills multiple roles. It vacates a5 for his knight, puts pressure on Be3  (stopping f3)  and hits a2. We can use the fact that f3 is impossible by playing ...Bg4. }
13. Qd2 { A natural move, but now white's centre comes under heavy fire. }
13... Rd8 14. d5 { A concession - e5 is a great square for the knight. } 14...
Ne5 15. Bb5 Bd7
{ The exchange benefits black, but isn't black just losing his queen... } 16.
Bc5 { Black's queen is trapped. } 16... Qxc1+ 17. Nxc1
{ Taking with the queen leads to even greater problems. } 17... Bxb5+ 18. Kg1
e6
{ Black is down a tiny bit of material, but has huge compensation - namely white's dead rook. }
*

