[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange - Bc4 & Ne2"]
[Black "10.0-0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ This, followed up by 8. Ne2, is considered to be one of, if not the main lines of the Grunfeld. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2
{ White's agressive setup is one of his most promising in the Grunfeld. His pieces all develop naturally, like ...Be3, ... Qd2, ...O-O and ...Rc1 etc. He is now very well-placed to take support the centre and keep it. This whole setup gives Black other options as well though - like putting the bishop on c4 makes it vulnerable to ideas such as ...Na5. }
8... c5
{ Other ideas, such as ...b6 and ...Nc6 are slow and not very critical. } 9.
Be3 Nc6 10. O-O Qc7
{ One of the oldest systems in the 7. Bc4 Exchange. The most played move is the ultra-sharp and theoretical 10. ..Bg4, followed by this one. The complications are unnecessary though, and Black can good game using this line too. Understanding here is just as important as variations. The text move is a multipurpose one. We vacate the d8 square for our rook, where it can attack d4. This variation is unusual since in many cases black can deviate from theory but still have a decent game. Decent examples are playing e6 or b6 now instead of Qc7. }
11. Qc1
{ A move which does have some sense. White wants to put his rook on d1 to protect the d4 pawn, avoiding the annoying pin on the queen by the rook on d8. This move discoordinates white's pieces though. }
11... b6
{ Black decides to use the downside of White's last move: if Black's pieces are on the c-file, he will be able to take over it. So we plan to develop with ...Bb7, ...Rac8, ...Rfd8 and take on d4 at the right moment to get control of the c file and a good position. }
12. Rb1 Bb7 13. Bb5 Rfd8 14. f3 a6 15. Bxc6 Bxc6
{ White's centre is compensated by Black's bishop pair. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange - Bc4 & Ne2"]
[Black "10.0-0 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ This, followed up by 8. Ne2, is considered to be one of, if not the main lines of the Grunfeld. }
7... O-O 8. Ne2
{ White's agressive setup is one of his most promising in the Grunfeld. His pieces all develop naturally, like ...Be3, ... Qd2, ...O-O and ...Rc1 etc. He is now very well-placed to take support the centre and keep it. This whole setup gives Black other options as well though - like putting the bishop on c4 makes it vulnerable to ideas such as ...Na5. }
8... c5
{ Other ideas, such as ...b6 and ...Nc6 are slow and not very critical. } 9.
Be3 Nc6 10. O-O Qc7
{ One of the oldest systems in the 7. Bc4 Exchange. The most played move is the ultra-sharp and theoretical 10. ..Bg4, followed by this one. The complications are unnecessary though, and Black can good game using this line too. Understanding here is just as important as variations. The text move is a multipurpose one. We vacate the d8 square for our rook, where it can attack d4. This variation is unusual since in many cases black can deviate from theory but still have a decent game. Decent examples are playing e6 or b6 now instead of Qc7. }
11. Rc1
{ White has a large number of alternatives, but often black can reply with natural moves like ...e6, ...b6, ...Bb7 and so on. }
11... b6
{ This is a rare but good move. It is recommended by both Avrukh and Kaufman ! The idea is generally to play ...e5 to close the centre and manoeuvre the knight to d6 via a5 and b7. Black can then generate counterplay with ...f5 and ...bRd8 is most common but it makes since to keep the rook on f8 to support future kingside play. }
12. Bf4
{ This is a surprisingly common inaccuracy. White provokes ...e5 which black intends to play anyway. }
12... e5 13. Bg3 { White hopes to retain the pin and some pressure. } 13... Qe7
{ The queen fortunately has another good square on e7 where is is invulnerable to white's bishop. }
