{ White's most flexible move and one which is useful to have in your repertoire. It is often deployed specifically to target certain openings, and unfortunately the Grunfeld happens to be one of them. The bulk of this chapter will be covering the lines when white follows up with c4. }
1... Nf6 2. c4
{ This is known as the anti-Grunfeld. White makes a point of delaying or ommitting d4, which can cause all sorts of problems if black continues on 'autopilot'. I spent a while considering the options here for black. 1. The normal 'anti-Grunfeld' variation with ...g6 and ...d5 is the obvious choice. 2. A ... b6 setup which aims for a double fianchetto   ...g6  setup. This was advocated by Kaufman  (who cites Tiviakov as the pioneer)  . I've decided to go for the second option which I will explain on the next move. }
2... b6
{ As mentioned, I first encountered this idea in Kaufman's repertoire and I really liked it. I've decided to recommend this idea while expanding on his analysis. The positions are fresh, interesting and I believe it is objectively strong as well. The added practical benefit of playing like this is the surprise and 'better preparation' effect - most white anti-Grunfeld players would be expecting one of their very theoretical mainlines and would be well-prepared for it. By playing this, we avoid their theoretical knowledge and take play into different waters. The downside of playing like this is 3. d4 followed by 4. Nc3, which takes play into a Queen's Indian. Fortunately, this variation is not that challenging and black should equalise without much difficulty. }
3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 g6 5. d4 Bg7
{ The bishop on g7 as oppossed to e7 adds some interesting dynamic possibilities, such as the ...e5 or ...c5 breaks. }
6. O-O O-O
{ This position can be reached via a number of different move orders. Carlsen managed to beat Aronian as black from this position, albeit he arrived here via a different move order. From here white can branch off in a number of different directions. }
7. Qc2
{ The queen prepares for the knights arrival on c3 by taking e4 under control. }
7... e6 8. Nc3 d5
{ Black needs to change plan here - ...d5 is necessary to regain control over e4. }
9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bg5 Na6
{ Black's development scheme seems a bit unusual but it works. Next black plans to step out of the pin with ...Qe8 and then play ...Ne4. }
