{ As mentioned, I first encountered this idea in Kaufman's repertoire and I really liked it. I've decided to recommend this idea while expanding on his analysis. The positions are fresh, interesting and I believe it is objectively strong as well. The added practical benefit of playing like this is the surprise and 'better preparation' effect - most white anti-Grunfeld players would be expecting one of their very theoretical mainlines and would be well-prepared for it. By playing this, we avoid their theoretical knowledge and take play into different waters. The downside of playing like this is 3. d4 followed by 4. Nc3, which takes play into a Queen's Indian. Fortunately, this variation is not that challenging and black should equalise without much difficulty. }
