1. d4
{ Against the d4 deviations white can throw at us, I've realised that it's best to go for lines which are low-theory, safe and solid. There's already enough theory as it is in the Grunfeld without learning more against rare white tries. }
1... Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky was popularised by a handful of English GMs. It was known as the second best try for an advantage in the closed games   1.d4  after the Queen's Gambit. }
2... d5
{ Just like against the Veresov, the Bxf6 exchange is to black's advantage. }
3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 Be6 5. Bd3 c5 6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. c3 Nc6
{ Black's bishop pair makes up for his slightly fragmented pawn structure. } *

