1. d4
{ Against the d4 deviations white can throw at us, I've realised that it's best to go for lines which are low-theory, safe and solid. There's already enough theory as it is in the Grunfeld without learning more against rare white tries. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4
{ This is known as the London System. It has a tendency to be dry and boring, especially if black responds by putting his pawn on d5. Instead, black should seek a central break with ...d6 and ...c5/...e5. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 { White is a little bit ambitious and wants to play e4. } 4...
O-O 5. e4 d5 { We allow e4 so we can get some central tension after ...d5. } 6.
e5 Nfd7 { Black will continue in the style of the French with ...c5. } *

